Note:
Linux ARM64 (AArch64) System Call Implementation

This file implements low-level system calls for Linux ARM64 (AArch64) architecture.

Platform-specific details:
- OS: Linux
- Architecture: ARM64 (AArch64)
- Syscall convention: X8 = syscall number, X0-X7 = arguments
- Syscall instruction: svc #0
- Return value: X0 (negative values indicate errors)

ARM64 syscall ABI:
- Syscall number in X8 register
- Arguments in X0, X1, X2, X3, X4, X5, X6, X7 (up to 8 arguments)
- Return value in X0
- Syscall invoked with "svc #0" instruction
- Registers X0-X18 are caller-saved
- Error indicated by negative return value in X0

Linux ARM64 uses the Linux asm-generic syscall numbering (NOT x86_64 numbering).
Reference: Linux kernel arch/arm64/include/asm/unistd.h, which is itself a
thin wrapper over include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h. Examples: SYS_IO_SETUP=0,
SYS_READ=63, SYS_WRITE=64, SYS_OPENAT=56 (note: there is no SYS_OPEN on
arm64 - userland must call openat with AT_FDCWD). This differs fundamentally
from x86_64 where SYS_READ=0 and SYS_WRITE=1.
:End Note

Note:
============================================================================
SYSCALL NUMBER CONSTANTS (Linux ARM64 / asm-generic numbering)
============================================================================
These syscall numbers use the Linux asm-generic numbering (NOT the same
as x86_64). On arm64, SYS_READ=63, SYS_WRITE=64; on x86_64 the same
operations are SYS_READ=0, SYS_WRITE=1. Reference:
include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h in the Linux kernel source.
:End Note

