Process called "linux_arm64_sys_access" takes filename as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native access(2). Bridges to faccessat(2) by
    prepending AT_FDCWD (-100) to the argument list. SYS_ACCESS
    accessor returns 48 (__NR_faccessat). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    faccessat(AT_FDCWD, filename, mode).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD=-100, filename, mode). Constructs
    AT_FDCWD as (0 minus 100) since literal -100 is not a Runa
    syntactic form for negative integer literals; result is the
    integer value -100 which sign-extends to 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFF9C in
    the x0 register, exactly matching POSIX AT_FDCWD.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One extra register load (AT_FDCWD constant) vs a native access()
    syscall on x86_64. Kernel-side cost identical; same do_faccessat
    backend.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    filename pointer validated by kernel via strncpy_from_user
    bounded by PATH_MAX. Mode bits (F_OK/R_OK/W_OK/X_OK) validated
    by kernel; invalid bits produce -EINVAL. Real-uid vs
    effective-uid semantics match legacy access() (real-uid check),
    not the AT_EACCESS variant.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_ACCESS()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, filename, mode)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_pipe" takes pipefd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native pipe(2). Bridges to pipe2(2) with flags=0,
    matching legacy pipe() semantics exactly. SYS_PIPE accessor
    returns 59 (__NR_pipe2). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    pipe2(pipefd, 0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-argument syscall: (pipefd, 0). The 0 flags argument disables
    O_CLOEXEC and O_NONBLOCK, matching pipe() defaults exactly. The
    kernel writes the read-end FD into pipefd[0] and write-end FD
    into pipefd[1].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Identical kernel-side cost to legacy pipe(); one extra register
    load (flags=0) on the user side. Inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    pipefd user-pointer validated by kernel via copy_to_user; bad
    pointer produces -EFAULT. FDs returned are subject to
    RLIMIT_NOFILE.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_PIPE()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, pipefd, 0)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_select" takes nfds as Integer, readfds as Integer, writefds as Integer, exceptfds as Integer, timeout as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native select(2). Bridges to pselect6(2) with
    sigmask=NULL, matching select() semantics. SYS_SELECT accessor
    returns 72 (__NR_pselect6). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    pselect6(nfds, readfds, writefds, exceptfds, timeout_as_timespec,
    NULL). The caller is responsible for converting timeout from
    struct timeval to struct timespec if applicable; this wrapper
    passes the timeout pointer through verbatim.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Six-argument syscall: (nfds, readfds, writefds, exceptfds,
    timeout, 0). The 6th argument is the sigmask wrapper-struct
    pointer; 0 means no sigmask manipulation, matching select()
    semantics where the calling thread's existing sigmask is
    unchanged.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Kernel-side cost is O(nfds) - the kernel scans fd_set bitmaps
    up to nfds bits. pselect6 has identical cost to legacy
    select. For high-fd workloads, prefer epoll.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd_set pointers validated by kernel via copy_from_user /
    copy_to_user. timeout pointer validated. The NULL sigmask
    pointer means no atomic sigmask install/uninstall - callers
    needing race-free sigmask handling must call pselect6
    directly.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_SELECT()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_6(syscall_num, nfds, readfds, writefds, exceptfds, timeout, 0)
End Process

