Process called "linux_arm64_sys_dup2" takes oldfd as Integer, newfd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native dup2(2). Bridges to dup3(2) with flags=0,
    which yields identical semantics EXCEPT for the oldfd==newfd
    edge case: legacy dup2 returns newfd unchanged; dup3 returns
    -EINVAL. This wrapper preserves legacy dup2 semantics by
    short-circuiting the equal-fd case. SYS_DUP2 accessor returns
    24 (__NR_dup3). POSIX-equivalent invocation: dup3(oldfd,
    newfd, 0) with the equal-fd legacy carve-out.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-argument syscall: (oldfd, newfd, 0). Before the syscall,
    if oldfd equals newfd, returns newfd directly without
    invoking the kernel - matching legacy dup2(fd, fd) semantics
    where the result is simply fd. Otherwise dispatches dup3.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Equal-fd fast path avoids the syscall entirely. Normal path is
    O(1) - one FD-table slot operation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    oldfd validated by kernel against the FD table. newfd, if
    out of RLIMIT_NOFILE range, produces -EBADF. If newfd was
    already open, dup3 closes it silently before reassignment -
    standard dup2 behaviour.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_DUP2()
    If oldfd is equal to newfd:
        Return newfd
    End If
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, oldfd, newfd, 0)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_pause" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native pause(2). Bridges to ppoll(2) with all-NULL
    arguments, blocking the calling thread indefinitely until a
    signal is delivered. SYS_PAUSE accessor returns 73
    (__NR_ppoll). POSIX-equivalent invocation: ppoll(NULL, 0,
    NULL, NULL, 0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (0, 0, 0, 0, 0) corresponding to
    (ufds=NULL, nfds=0, tsp=NULL, sigmask=NULL, sigsetsize=0).
    Kernel transitions thread to TASK_INTERRUPTIBLE and waits
    until signal arrival, then returns -EINTR.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) kernel-side - no fd-set scanning, no timer setup, no
    sigmask manipulation. Wake cost is one signal delivery.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user-pointer dereferences (all args 0/NULL). Wake
    conditions are signal-delivery only; subject to the
    process's signal-disposition table and active sigmask.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_PAUSE()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_nanosleep" takes req as Integer, rem as Integer returns Integer:
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_NANOSLEEP()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, req, rem)
End Process

