Process called "linux_arm64_sys_fork" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native fork(2). Bridges to clone(2) with
    flags=SIGCHLD only, which produces a new process with its own
    address space (full COW), its own FD table, and SIGCHLD
    delivered to the parent on child exit - byte-equivalent to
    legacy fork(). SYS_FORK accessor returns 220 (__NR_clone).
    POSIX-equivalent invocation: clone(SIGCHLD, NULL, NULL, NULL,
    NULL).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (SIGCHLD=17, 0, 0, 0, 0) corresponding
    to (flags, stack, parent_tid, child_tid, tls). On arm64 the
    clone argument order is (flags, stack, parent_tid, tls,
    child_tid), but since all variadic args are 0 the order is
    moot. SIGCHLD numeric value is 17 per
    include/uapi/asm-generic/signal.h.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side fork is one of the
    most expensive syscalls (page-table COW, FD-table copy,
    signal-handler copy); clone-with-SIGCHLD hits the same path.
    No bridge overhead vs native fork.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Subject to RLIMIT_NPROC and cgroup pids.max. Child inherits
    credentials unchanged; subsequent setuid/setgid in the child
    is the standard privilege-drop mechanism.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_FORK()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, 17, 0, 0, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_vfork" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native vfork(2). Bridges to clone(2) with
    flags=CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK|SIGCHLD (=0x100|0x4000|17=16657),
    which produces a child sharing the parent's address space
    while suspending the parent until the child execs or exits -
    byte-equivalent to legacy vfork(). SYS_VFORK accessor returns
    220 (__NR_clone). POSIX-equivalent invocation: clone(16657,
    NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL). This is exactly what glibc's
    arm64 vfork() wrapper does.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (16657, 0, 0, 0, 0). The composite
    flag value decomposes as CLONE_VM (0x100 = 256) | CLONE_VFORK
    (0x4000 = 16384) | SIGCHLD (17). Sum: 256 + 16384 + 17 =
    16657. References: include/uapi/linux/sched.h for CLONE_VM
    and CLONE_VFORK; include/uapi/asm-generic/signal.h for
    SIGCHLD.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cheaper than fork because CLONE_VM skips page-table COW
    setup. CLONE_VFORK adds a parent-blocking completion-wait
    for child exec/exit. Modern code should prefer
    posix_spawn() over vfork.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Subject to same RLIMIT_NPROC and cgroup limits as fork. The
    shared-address-space window is a foot-gun: POSIX prohibits
    the child from doing anything other than _exit() or exec*()
    before the parent resumes. This rule is caller-side
    discipline, not kernel-enforced.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_VFORK()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, 16657, 0, 0, 0, 0)
End Process

