Process called "linux_arm64_sys_rename" takes oldpath as Integer, newpath as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native rename(2). Bridges to renameat(2) with
    olddirfd=AT_FDCWD and newdirfd=AT_FDCWD. SYS_RENAME accessor
    returns 38 (__NR_renameat). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    renameat(AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath).
    AT_FDCWD constructed as (0 minus 100) to obtain -100.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    cross-directory journal operations (journaled FSes) or
    directory-entry swap (in-memory FSes). Atomic across power
    loss on journaled FSes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on both source and destination parent
    directories. Cross-filesystem rename returns -EXDEV; the
    caller must fall back to copy+unlink in that case.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_RENAME()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_4(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, oldpath, at_fdcwd, newpath)
End Process

