Process called "linux_arm64_sys_link" takes oldpath as Integer, newpath as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native link(2). Bridges to linkat(2) with
    olddirfd=AT_FDCWD, newdirfd=AT_FDCWD, and flags=0. SYS_LINK
    accessor returns 37 (__NR_linkat). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    linkat(AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath, 0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath,
    0). AT_FDCWD constructed as (0 minus 100). Flags=0 disables
    AT_SYMLINK_FOLLOW; linkat with flags=0 follows symlinks for
    oldpath the same way legacy link() does.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    inode refcount increment and directory-entry insertion.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on the destination directory required.
    Post-Linux-3.6, the protected_hardlinks sysctl enforces that
    the caller own the source file or have read/write permission
    on it - a TOCTOU-hardening measure against /tmp-attack
    scenarios.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_LINK()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, oldpath, at_fdcwd, newpath, 0)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_unlink" takes pathname as Integer returns Integer:
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_UNLINK()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, pathname)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_symlink" takes target as Integer, linkpath as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native symlink(2). Bridges to symlinkat(2) with
    newdirfd=AT_FDCWD. SYS_SYMLINK accessor returns 36
    (__NR_symlinkat). POSIX-equivalent invocation: symlinkat(target,
    AT_FDCWD, linkpath). Note the argument order: target comes
    FIRST, then dirfd, then linkpath - inverse of the
    open/access/etc. pattern.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-argument syscall: (target, AT_FDCWD, linkpath). AT_FDCWD
    constructed as (0 minus 100). The target string is stored
    verbatim in the symlink inode; it is NOT resolved at
    creation time.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by symlink-inode allocation
    and directory-entry insertion.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on the parent directory of linkpath
    required. The target string is stored verbatim and is NOT
    validated against PATH_MAX or existence (symlink-to-nothing
    is legal). Path-traversal hazards arise on read, not
    creation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_SYMLINK()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, target, at_fdcwd, linkpath)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_readlink" takes pathname as Integer, buf as Integer, bufsiz as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native readlink(2). Bridges to readlinkat(2) with
    dirfd=AT_FDCWD. SYS_READLINK accessor returns 78
    (__NR_readlinkat). POSIX-equivalent invocation:
    readlinkat(AT_FDCWD, pathname, buf, bufsiz).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, buf, bufsiz).
    AT_FDCWD constructed as (0 minus 100). Return value is
    bytes copied (no NUL terminator written - caller's
    responsibility).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    symlink-target string copy, bounded by min(bufsiz, target_len).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read permission on the parent directory required for
    resolution. Truncation occurs silently if buf is smaller
    than target - caller must use lstat() to discover st_size
    first or retry with larger buffers.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_READLINK()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_4(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, pathname, buf, bufsiz)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_sys_chmod" takes pathname as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native chmod(2). Bridges to fchmodat(2) with
    dirfd=AT_FDCWD. SYS_CHMOD accessor returns 53 (__NR_fchmodat).
    POSIX-equivalent invocation: fchmodat(AT_FDCWD, pathname,
    mode, 0). The kernel syscall is 3-arg (dirfd, path, mode);
    the flags argument visible at the glibc API is a libc-level
    extension not present at the ABI.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, mode). AT_FDCWD
    constructed as (0 minus 100).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by inode lookup and
    permission update.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must be the file owner or have CAP_FOWNER. Set-uid /
    set-gid bits are silently cleared on non-owning chmod.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_CHMOD()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, pathname, mode)
End Process

