Process called "linux_arm64_sys_chown" takes pathname as Integer, owner as Integer, group as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native chown(2). Bridges to fchownat(2) with
    dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0 (follow symlinks). SYS_CHOWN
    accessor returns 54 (__NR_fchownat). POSIX-equivalent
    invocation: fchownat(AT_FDCWD, pathname, owner, group, 0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, owner, group, 0).
    AT_FDCWD constructed as (0 minus 100). Flags=0 follows
    symlinks, matching legacy chown() semantics.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    inode metadata update.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Requires CAP_CHOWN for arbitrary owner/group changes;
    unprivileged callers can only change group to a
    supplementary group. Set-uid / set-gid bits silently cleared
    per POSIX.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_CHOWN()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, pathname, owner, group, 0)
End Process

