Process called "linux_arm64_sys_lchown" takes pathname as Integer, owner as Integer, group as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    arm64 has no native lchown(2). Bridges to fchownat(2) with
    dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW (0x100=256),
    which causes the kernel to change ownership of the symlink
    itself rather than its target - the defining lchown vs chown
    distinction. SYS_LCHOWN accessor returns 54 (__NR_fchownat).
    POSIX-equivalent invocation: fchownat(AT_FDCWD, pathname,
    owner, group, AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-argument syscall: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, owner, group, 256).
    AT_FDCWD constructed as (0 minus 100). The flag value 256
    is AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW per include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Same kernel-side profile as chown; the flag is a
    single conditional inside do_fchownat.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same CAP_CHOWN requirement as chown. lchown is the
    security-correct primitive for changing symlink ownership
    without traversing it - using chown on a symlink is a
    classic TOCTOU foot-gun.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_LCHOWN()
    Let at_fdcwd be 0 minus 100
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_5(syscall_num, at_fdcwd, pathname, owner, group, 256)
End Process

