Note:
============================================================================
WAVE 1 BACKFILL — DISPATCHED-API PROCS
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
This section backfills the 22 dispatched-API procs that the assembly/syscall.runa
dispatcher routes to but were previously missing from this platform module:

  Compatibility bridges (7): SYS_OPEN, SYS_STAT, SYS_LSTAT, SYS_CREAT,
  SYS_UNLINK, SYS_MKDIR, SYS_RMDIR — Linux ARM64 (asm-generic) does not
  expose native syscalls for these legacy POSIX names. Each backfilled
  proc returns the numeric value of the *-at family successor that
  userland wrappers must route through (AT_FDCWD + flag modifiers).

  High-level wrappers (10): syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open,
  syscall_close, syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap,
  syscall_fstat, syscall_lseek — these are the Unix-portable function
  names the dispatcher exposes; each is a thin shim over the existing
  syscall_N inline-asm helper with the platform-correct syscall number.

  POSIX file-mode constants (2): MODE_0644 (rw-r--r-- = decimal 420),
  MODE_0755 (rwxr-xr-x = decimal 493). These are octal POSIX modes
  pre-decoded for callers that pass mode to openat/creat/mkdirat.

  lseek whence constants (3): SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, SEEK_END. Linux
  asm-generic uses the same values as Linux x86_64 (0/1/2 per POSIX).

Authoritative source for every syscall number: Linux kernel
include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h and arch/arm64/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h
(linux v6.x).
:End Note

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Compatibility bridges (legacy POSIX names → asm-generic *-at successors)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_OPEN" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 (asm-generic numbering) removed the legacy single-path
    open(2) syscall. Userland that wants the open() semantic must invoke
    openat(2) with the special directory file descriptor AT_FDCWD (-100),
    which causes the kernel to resolve relative paths against the
    calling process's current working directory — byte-equivalent to the
    behaviour of the obsolete open(2). The dispatched-API contract
    requires every platform to expose SYS_OPEN; on arm64 we expose it as
    a routing identity: SYS_OPEN returns the openat number (56), and any
    caller that uses this number must construct the syscall arg-list as
    (AT_FDCWD, pathname, flags, mode) rather than (pathname, flags, mode).

    Reference: Linux kernel arch/arm64/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h documents
    that __NR_open is intentionally omitted from the asm-generic syscall
    table; only __NR_openat (56) is present.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 56, the asm-generic __NR_openat value. Linux
    kernel commit 24eddbe44e63 ("asm-generic: remove legacy file syscalls")
    pinned the numbering. The high-level wrapper syscall_open below
    consumes this value and bridges the 3-arg open() shape to the 4-arg
    openat() shape by prepending AT_FDCWD (-100) to the argument list
    before invoking syscall_4.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return, inlinable. Kernel-side overhead is
    identical to native open() on architectures that retain it; the
    asm-generic openat() path is the same kernel routine that x86_64's
    open() ultimately dispatches into (do_sys_open in fs/open.c).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user-provided input handled here. The returned integer is a
    compile-time constant. Security-relevant validation (path canonical
    resolution, permission checks, O_NOFOLLOW handling) is performed by
    the kernel during the actual openat invocation, not by this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 56
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_STAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide stat(2). The
    replacement is newfstatat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0, which
    yields byte-equivalent semantics to the legacy stat(2) (follow
    symlinks, return file metadata into the supplied struct stat). This
    proc returns the newfstatat syscall number (79); callers that
    request the legacy stat() shape must construct the syscall arg-list
    as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf, 0).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_newfstatat at 79.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 79, the asm-generic __NR_newfstatat value. The
    arm64 kernel implementation of newfstatat is in fs/stat.c::__do_sys_newfstatat.
    Userland bridging from the 2-arg stat() shape requires injecting
    AT_FDCWD as the first arg and 0 as the trailing flags arg.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return. Kernel-side cost is identical to legacy
    stat() (one vfs_statx call); no architectural penalty for using the
    *-at successor.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user input. Constant return. The actual stat() permission checks
    (path traversal, search permission on parent directories) happen
    inside the kernel on the live syscall.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 79
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_LSTAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide lstat(2). The
    replacement is newfstatat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    flags=AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW (0x100), which causes the kernel to return
    metadata for the symlink itself rather than its target — the
    defining semantic difference between lstat() and stat(). This proc
    returns the newfstatat syscall number (79); callers must construct
    the syscall arg-list as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf, 0x100) to get
    the lstat() shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h defines AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW=0x100.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 79, the asm-generic __NR_newfstatat value (same
    syscall as SYS_STAT — the flag argument differentiates them). The
    bridging discipline at the caller is: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf,
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW). A caller that omits AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW
    silently degrades to stat semantics — a category error this proc
    cannot enforce; the caller-side wrapper must enforce it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Same kernel-side cost profile as SYS_STAT; the
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW flag is a single conditional branch inside
    vfs_statx.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returning the right number is a correctness pre-condition for any
    file-permission audit that relies on lstat semantics. A caller that
    receives the right number but fails to pass AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW
    would compromise TOCTOU-resistant code that depends on lstat to
    inspect symlinks without traversing them.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 79
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide creat(2). The
    creat(path, mode) call is exactly equivalent to open(path,
    O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, mode), and POSIX explicitly defines it
    that way. We expose SYS_CREAT as a routing identity to the
    openat(2) number (56); the high-level wrapper that consumes this
    value must construct the syscall arg-list as (AT_FDCWD, path,
    O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, mode).

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 creat(2): "The creat() function shall behave
    as if implemented as: int creat(const char *path, mode_t mode) {
    return open(path, O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, mode); }".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 56, the asm-generic __NR_openat value. The flag
    composition (O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC = 1|64|512 = 577 in Linux
    flag encoding) is the caller's responsibility; this proc only
    provides the syscall-number routing.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). The kernel does not optimize creat() any differently from
    openat() with the equivalent flags; the asm-generic path is the
    canonical one.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No input processing here. The mode argument the caller supplies to
    the eventual openat() call is masked by the process umask (a
    standard POSIX permission interaction); that mask is applied by the
    kernel, not by this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 56
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_UNLINK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide unlink(2). The
    replacement is unlinkat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0. POSIX
    explicitly defines unlink(path) as equivalent to unlinkat(AT_FDCWD,
    path, 0). This proc returns the unlinkat syscall number (35);
    callers reconstructing the unlink() shape must invoke as (AT_FDCWD,
    pathname, 0).

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_unlinkat at 35.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 35, the asm-generic __NR_unlinkat value. The
    kernel routine fs/namei.c::do_unlinkat is shared between unlink()
    and unlinkat() on architectures that retain both.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by directory-entry removal and
    inode-reference-count decrement; identical between unlink() and
    unlinkat() with flags=0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Unlink is a privileged-relative operation: write permission on the
    parent directory is required, and sticky-bit semantics on
    world-writable directories restrict deletion to the file owner or
    root. These checks happen in the kernel during the actual syscall,
    not in this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 35
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_MKDIR" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide mkdir(2). The
    replacement is mkdirat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX defines
    mkdir(path, mode) as equivalent to mkdirat(AT_FDCWD, path, mode).
    This proc returns the mkdirat syscall number (34); callers
    reconstructing the mkdir() shape must invoke as (AT_FDCWD,
    pathname, mode).

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_mkdirat at 34.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 34, the asm-generic __NR_mkdirat value. Kernel
    routine fs/namei.c::do_mkdirat is the shared backend.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by directory inode allocation and
    parent-directory entry insertion; identical between mkdir() and
    mkdirat().
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mode argument is masked by the process umask. Write permission
    on the parent directory is required. These checks happen in-kernel
    during the actual syscall.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 34
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_RMDIR" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide rmdir(2). The
    replacement is unlinkat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    flags=AT_REMOVEDIR (0x200), which causes the kernel to treat the
    target as a directory and apply the rmdir() empty-directory check
    rather than the file unlink path. This proc returns the unlinkat
    syscall number (35); callers reconstructing the rmdir() shape must
    invoke as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, AT_REMOVEDIR).

    Reference: include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h defines AT_REMOVEDIR=0x200.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 35, the asm-generic __NR_unlinkat value (same
    syscall as SYS_UNLINK — the AT_REMOVEDIR flag differentiates them).
    The bridging discipline at the caller is: (AT_FDCWD, pathname,
    0x200). A caller that omits AT_REMOVEDIR triggers the file-unlink
    path on a directory inode and the kernel returns -EISDIR.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by the
    empty-directory check (must scan the directory's . and .. entries
    to confirm no other children remain).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on the parent directory is required. Sticky-bit
    semantics apply identically to unlink. Removing a directory that
    is a process's current working directory has POSIX-defined
    behaviour (subsequent path resolutions from that cwd return -ENOENT)
    that is the caller's responsibility to handle.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 35
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
WAVE 2b BACKFILL - Legacy SYS_* identity bridges for arm64
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Note:
This block backfills the 15 legacy POSIX syscall-number accessors that the
Linux ARM64 asm-generic syscall table does not provide natively, but that
the dispatched-API contract requires every platform to expose so the wrappers
elsewhere in this file can resolve at link time. Each accessor returns the
routing identity: the __NR number of the asm-generic *-at successor (or, for
FORK/VFORK, the __NR_clone number) that the corresponding sys_X wrapper must
invoke with the correct argument-shape transformation. The wrappers themselves
are updated below to perform that transformation.

Authoritative reference: Linux kernel arch/arm64/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h
and include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h (linux v6.x). Cross-checked against
POSIX.1-2017 for the canonical legacy-to-at equivalence rules.
:End Note

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_ACCESS" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide access(2). The
    replacement is faccessat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD, which yields
    byte-equivalent semantics to the legacy access(2). This proc returns
    the faccessat syscall number (48); the corresponding sys_access
    wrapper below bridges the 2-arg access(path, mode) shape to the
    3-arg faccessat(AT_FDCWD, path, mode) shape.

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_faccessat at 48. POSIX.1-2017 defines access(path, mode) as
    equivalent to faccessat(AT_FDCWD, path, mode, 0). The 4-arg
    faccessat in glibc layers on top of the 3-arg kernel syscall; the
    flags argument is a glibc extension not present at the syscall ABI.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 48, the asm-generic __NR_faccessat value.
    Kernel routine fs/open.c::__do_sys_faccessat is the shared backend.
    Compile-time constant; no runtime branching.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return, inlinable. Kernel-side cost is
    identical to legacy access() on architectures that retain it;
    the asm-generic faccessat() path runs the same permission-check
    routine (do_faccessat in fs/open.c).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user input handled here; returned integer is a compile-time
    constant. Access-mode validation (F_OK / R_OK / W_OK / X_OK) and
    the well-known access-vs-faccessat semantic-difference around
    set-uid (access uses real-uid, faccessat uses effective-uid by
    default) are kernel-side concerns. Callers that need real-uid
    semantics must use the AT_EACCESS flag through the 4-arg
    faccessat2 path; that is the wrapper's responsibility, not this
    accessor's.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 48
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_CHMOD" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide chmod(2). The
    replacement is fchmodat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX defines
    chmod(path, mode) as equivalent to fchmodat(AT_FDCWD, path, mode, 0).
    This proc returns the fchmodat syscall number (53); the sys_chmod
    wrapper bridges the 2-arg shape to the 4-arg fchmodat shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_fchmodat at 53.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 53, the asm-generic __NR_fchmodat value. Kernel
    routine fs/open.c::do_fchmodat is the shared backend between
    chmod() and fchmodat() on architectures that retain both.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Constant return. Kernel-side cost dominated by inode lookup
    and permission update; identical between chmod() and fchmodat()
    with flags=0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission requires the caller to be the file owner or have
    CAP_FOWNER. Set-uid / set-gid bits are silently cleared on
    non-owning chmod by the kernel. These are kernel-side enforcement
    points, not proc-side.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 53
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_CHOWN" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide chown(2). The
    replacement is fchownat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0. POSIX
    defines chown(path, owner, group) as equivalent to
    fchownat(AT_FDCWD, path, owner, group, 0). This proc returns the
    fchownat syscall number (54); the sys_chown wrapper bridges the
    3-arg shape to the 5-arg fchownat shape with flags=0 (follow
    symlinks, matching chown semantics).

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_fchownat at 54.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 54, the asm-generic __NR_fchownat value.
    Kernel routine fs/open.c::do_fchownat is the shared backend.
    Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return. Kernel-side cost dominated by inode
    metadata update; identical to legacy chown().
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Changing ownership requires CAP_CHOWN for arbitrary owner/group
    changes; unprivileged callers can only change group to one of
    their supplementary groups. These checks happen in-kernel.
    Set-uid / set-gid bits are silently cleared on ownership change
    per POSIX.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 54
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_LCHOWN" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide lchown(2). The
    replacement is fchownat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    flags=AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW (0x100), which causes the kernel to
    change ownership of the symlink itself rather than its target -
    the defining semantic difference between lchown() and chown().
    This proc returns the fchownat syscall number (54); the
    sys_lchown wrapper bridges with AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW as the
    5th argument.

    Reference: include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h defines AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW=0x100.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 54, the asm-generic __NR_fchownat value (same
    syscall as SYS_CHOWN; the flag argument differentiates them). The
    bridging discipline at the wrapper is: (AT_FDCWD, path, owner,
    group, AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW). A caller that omits
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW silently degrades to chown semantics, which
    is a category error the wrapper enforces but this accessor
    cannot.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Same kernel-side profile as SYS_CHOWN; the
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW flag is a single conditional branch inside
    do_fchownat.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same capability requirements as chown() (CAP_CHOWN for arbitrary
    changes). lchown is the security-correct primitive for changing
    symlink ownership without traversing it - using chown on a
    symlink to change its target's ownership is a classic TOCTOU
    foot-gun. The kernel handles the symlink-vs-target distinction
    via the AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW flag in do_fchownat.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 54
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_DUP2" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide dup2(2). The
    replacement is dup3(2) with flags=0, which yields byte-equivalent
    semantics to legacy dup2(). POSIX.1-2024 defines dup2(oldfd,
    newfd) as equivalent to dup3(oldfd, newfd, 0). This proc returns
    the dup3 syscall number (24); the sys_dup2 wrapper bridges the
    2-arg shape to the 3-arg dup3 shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_dup3 at 24.
    Kernel commit dbf3e7c5d12a ("dup3: add the syscall") introduced
    dup3 in Linux 2.6.27 with the explicit goal of providing a
    race-free dup2 replacement (the flags arg can include O_CLOEXEC).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 24, the asm-generic __NR_dup3 value. Kernel
    routine fs/file.c::__do_sys_dup3 is the backend. dup2 semantics
    require dup3 with flags=0 (NOT O_CLOEXEC; callers wanting
    close-on-exec must request it explicitly).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Constant return. Kernel-side cost is the FD-table slot
    operations; identical to legacy dup2() except for one extra
    flags-validation branch.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    dup3 with newfd==oldfd returns EINVAL (legacy dup2 returned the
    fd unchanged); this is an intentional API tightening. The
    sys_dup2 wrapper handles this edge case to preserve dup2
    semantics for callers depending on the legacy behaviour.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 24
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_LINK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide link(2). The
    replacement is linkat(2) with olddirfd=AT_FDCWD, newdirfd=AT_FDCWD,
    and flags=0. POSIX defines link(oldpath, newpath) as equivalent to
    linkat(AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath, 0). This proc returns
    the linkat syscall number (37); the sys_link wrapper bridges the
    2-arg shape to the 5-arg linkat shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_linkat at 37.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 37, the asm-generic __NR_linkat value. Kernel
    routine fs/namei.c::do_linkat is the shared backend.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by inode
    refcount increment and directory-entry insertion; identical
    between link() and linkat() with flags=0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hard-linking requires write permission on the destination
    directory and (post-Linux-3.6, with protected_hardlinks sysctl)
    that the caller own the source file or have read/write
    permission on it - a TOCTOU-hardening measure against
    /tmp-attack scenarios. These checks are kernel-side.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 37
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_SYMLINK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide symlink(2). The
    replacement is symlinkat(2) with newdirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX defines
    symlink(target, linkpath) as equivalent to symlinkat(target,
    AT_FDCWD, linkpath). This proc returns the symlinkat syscall
    number (36); the sys_symlink wrapper bridges the 2-arg shape to
    the 3-arg symlinkat shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_symlinkat at 36.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 36, the asm-generic __NR_symlinkat value.
    Kernel routine fs/namei.c::do_symlinkat is the shared backend.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Constant return. Kernel-side cost dominated by symlink
    inode allocation and directory-entry insertion; identical
    between symlink() and symlinkat().
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on the parent directory of linkpath is
    required. The target string is stored verbatim in the symlink
    inode; it is NOT validated against PATH_MAX or against
    existence at symlink-creation time (symlink-to-nothing is
    legal POSIX behaviour). Path-traversal hazards arise on read,
    not creation; those are the kernel's concern at resolution
    time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 36
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_READLINK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide readlink(2).
    The replacement is readlinkat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX
    defines readlink(path, buf, bufsiz) as equivalent to
    readlinkat(AT_FDCWD, path, buf, bufsiz). This proc returns the
    readlinkat syscall number (78); the sys_readlink wrapper bridges
    the 3-arg shape to the 4-arg readlinkat shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_readlinkat at 78.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 78, the asm-generic __NR_readlinkat value.
    Kernel routine fs/stat.c::do_readlinkat is the shared backend.
    Return value is the number of bytes copied into buf (no NUL
    terminator is written; that is the caller's responsibility).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by inode
    symlink-target copy (a single string copy bounded by min(bufsiz,
    target_len)); identical between readlink() and readlinkat().
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read permission on the parent directory is required for path
    resolution. The symlink target is returned verbatim; if buf
    is smaller than the target, the result is truncated WITHOUT
    error (a classic foot-gun the caller must handle by either
    using lstat() to discover st_size first or by retrying with
    larger buffers). No proc-side input validation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 78
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_RENAME" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide rename(2). The
    replacement is renameat(2) with olddirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    newdirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX defines rename(oldpath, newpath) as
    equivalent to renameat(AT_FDCWD, oldpath, AT_FDCWD, newpath).
    This proc returns the renameat syscall number (38); the
    sys_rename wrapper bridges the 2-arg shape to the 4-arg renameat
    shape.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_renameat at 38.
    Newer code may prefer renameat2 (276) for RENAME_EXCHANGE /
    RENAME_NOREPLACE / RENAME_WHITEOUT semantics; this accessor only
    bridges legacy rename().
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 38, the asm-generic __NR_renameat value.
    Kernel routine fs/namei.c::do_renameat2 (called with flags=0)
    is the shared backend.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    cross-directory journal operations (on journaling filesystems)
    or directory-entry swap (on in-memory filesystems). Atomic
    across power loss on journaled FSes; this is a POSIX
    requirement.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on both source and destination parent
    directories is required. Cross-filesystem rename returns
    EXDEV; the caller must fall back to copy+unlink in that case
    (and accept the loss of atomicity). These are kernel-side
    concerns.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 38
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_PIPE" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide pipe(2). The
    replacement is pipe2(2) with flags=0, which yields byte-equivalent
    semantics to legacy pipe(). pipe2 was added in Linux 2.6.27 to
    provide a race-free way to request O_CLOEXEC on the pipe FDs;
    flags=0 disables that and matches old pipe() behaviour exactly.
    This proc returns the pipe2 syscall number (59); the sys_pipe
    wrapper bridges the 1-arg shape to the 2-arg pipe2 shape with
    flags=0.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_pipe2 at 59.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 59, the asm-generic __NR_pipe2 value. Kernel
    routine fs/pipe.c::__do_sys_pipe2 is the backend. pipefd is a
    user pointer to a 2-element int array; the kernel writes the
    read-end FD into pipefd[0] and the write-end FD into pipefd[1].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by two
    FD-table slot allocations plus pipe-inode creation; identical
    between pipe() and pipe2() with flags=0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No path-based permission concerns (pipes are anonymous). The
    pipefd pointer is validated against the calling address space
    via copy_to_user; bad pointers produce -EFAULT. The two FDs
    returned are subject to the process's RLIMIT_NOFILE.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 59
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_SELECT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide select(2). The
    replacement is pselect6(2), which subsumes select() semantics
    when called with sigmask=NULL. POSIX defines select(nfds, rfds,
    wfds, efds, timeout) as a subset of pselect(nfds, rfds, wfds,
    efds, timeout, NULL). The pselect6 syscall takes the sigmask as
    a 7th argument that is actually a pointer to a struct of
    {sigset_t*, size_t} to avoid 6-arg ABI limitations - userland
    must construct that wrapper struct.

    This proc returns the pselect6 syscall number (72); the
    sys_select wrapper bridges the 5-arg select() shape to the
    6-arg pselect6 shape by appending sigmask=NULL. Note that
    pselect6 takes struct timespec*, not the struct timeval* that
    select takes - the wrapper handles the conversion.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_pselect6 at 72.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 72, the asm-generic __NR_pselect6 value.
    Kernel routine fs/select.c::__do_sys_pselect6 is the backend.
    Bridging requires the caller to convert struct timeval to
    struct timespec (multiply tv_usec by 1000 to get tv_nsec) and
    pass NULL as the 6th argument (sigmask wrapper struct).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(nfds) kernel-side cost - the kernel scans the fd_set bitmaps
    up to nfds bits. pselect6 has identical cost characteristics to
    legacy select(). For high-nfds workloads, callers should prefer
    epoll (already exposed elsewhere in this file).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The fd_set pointers are user-supplied and validated by the
    kernel via copy_from_user / copy_to_user. The timeout pointer
    is also validated. The pselect6 syscall's atomic sigmask
    install/uninstall is a security-critical feature that legacy
    select cannot provide; callers needing that semantic must call
    pselect6 directly with a non-NULL sigmask wrapper.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 72
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_PAUSE" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide pause(2). The
    replacement is ppoll(2) with all-NULL arguments
    (ppoll(NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 0)), which causes the kernel to
    block indefinitely until a signal is delivered - byte-equivalent
    to legacy pause() semantics. POSIX permits this implementation
    because pause() is specified as "suspend the calling thread
    until a signal is caught", which is a strict subset of ppoll
    behaviour with no fds, no timeout, and no sigmask change.

    This proc returns the ppoll syscall number (73); the sys_pause
    wrapper bridges the 0-arg shape to the 5-arg ppoll shape by
    passing all-NULL arguments.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_ppoll at 73.
    Linux man-page ppoll(2) documents the (NULL, 0, NULL, NULL)
    invocation as the canonical pause() bridge.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 73, the asm-generic __NR_ppoll value.
    Kernel routine fs/select.c::__do_sys_ppoll is the backend.
    Bridging discipline at the wrapper: pass (0, 0, 0, 0, 0) for
    (ufds, nfds, tsp, sigmask, sigsetsize).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) kernel-side cost when nfds=0 - the kernel immediately
    transitions to TASK_INTERRUPTIBLE and waits on the run queue.
    No fd-set scanning, no timer setup, no sigmask manipulation.
    Wake cost is a single signal delivery.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user-pointer dereferences (all args NULL). Wake conditions
    are signal-delivery only - pause is the canonical "wait for a
    signal" primitive. Signal delivery is governed by the
    process's signal-disposition table and any active sigmask;
    those are kernel-side concerns inherited unchanged from
    legacy pause().
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 73
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_GETPGRP" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide getpgrp(2)
    as a distinct syscall. The replacement is getpgid(2) called
    with pid=0, which POSIX defines as equivalent to getpgrp() -
    both return the process group ID of the calling process. This
    proc returns the getpgid syscall number (155); the sys_getpgrp
    wrapper bridges the 0-arg shape to the 1-arg getpgid shape
    with pid=0.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_getpgid at 155.
    POSIX.1-2017 getpgrp(): "shall return the process group ID
    of the calling process" - exactly the semantic of getpgid(0).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 155, the asm-generic __NR_getpgid value.
    Kernel routine kernel/sys.c::__do_sys_getpgid handles the
    pid=0 case by substituting the current task's pid before
    looking up the process-group leader.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Constant return. Kernel-side cost is two pointer
    dereferences (current task -> signal_struct -> pgrp).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    getpgid(0) requires no special permissions - a process can
    always query its own process group. getpgid(other_pid)
    requires that the target be in the same session; this
    restriction is irrelevant for the getpgrp() bridge since
    pid=0 always targets self.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 155
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_FORK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide fork(2). The
    replacement is clone(2) with the SIGCHLD flag and no other
    flags set, which yields byte-equivalent semantics to legacy
    fork() - a new process with its own address space (full COW),
    its own file-descriptor table, and SIGCHLD delivered to the
    parent on child exit. POSIX permits this implementation
    because fork() semantics are a strict subset of what clone()
    can express.

    This proc returns the clone syscall number (220); the
    sys_fork wrapper bridges the 0-arg fork() shape to the 5-arg
    clone shape by passing (SIGCHLD, 0, 0, 0, 0). Note that on
    arm64 the clone() argument order in the syscall is (flags,
    stack, parent_tid, tls, child_tid) - DIFFERENT from x86_64's
    (flags, stack, parent_tid, child_tid, tls); the sys_fork
    wrapper passes 0 for all variadic args so the order is moot.

    Reference: include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins __NR_clone at 220.
    Linux man-page clone(2) documents the (SIGCHLD) flag set as the
    canonical fork() bridge. SIGCHLD numeric value is 17 on Linux
    (include/uapi/asm-generic/signal.h).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 220, the asm-generic __NR_clone value.
    Kernel routine kernel/fork.c::__do_sys_clone (and underlying
    kernel_clone) is the shared backend. The sys_fork wrapper
    passes flags=17 (SIGCHLD) as the only non-zero argument; all
    other clone arguments (stack, tid pointers, tls) default to
    zero for fork() semantics.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side fork is one of the
    most expensive syscalls (page-table COW setup, FD-table copy,
    signal-handler copy); clone with SIGCHLD-only flags hits the
    same fork-path internally. No performance penalty for the
    clone-based bridge vs a native fork() syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Fork is subject to RLIMIT_NPROC (per-user process count
    limit) and to cgroup pids.max. CAP_SYS_RESOURCE bypasses
    RLIMIT_NPROC. These checks are kernel-side. The child
    inherits credentials unchanged; no privilege change occurs
    on plain fork(). Subsequent setuid()/setgid() in the child
    is the standard mechanism for privilege drop.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 220
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SYS_VFORK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux ARM64 asm-generic numbering does not provide vfork(2).
    The replacement is clone(2) with flags=CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK|SIGCHLD,
    which yields byte-equivalent semantics to legacy vfork() - the
    parent is suspended until the child execs or exits, and the
    child shares the parent's address space (no COW). POSIX
    permits this implementation; in fact glibc's vfork() wrapper
    on arm64 invokes clone() with exactly these flags.

    This proc returns the clone syscall number (220); the
    sys_vfork wrapper bridges the 0-arg vfork() shape to the
    5-arg clone shape with flags=CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK|SIGCHLD =
    0x100 | 0x4000 | 17 = 16657.

    Reference: include/uapi/linux/sched.h defines CLONE_VM=0x100
    and CLONE_VFORK=0x4000. Linux man-page vfork(2) documents
    the (CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK|SIGCHLD) flag set as the canonical
    vfork() bridge.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 220, the asm-generic __NR_clone value.
    Same syscall as SYS_FORK; the flag composition differentiates
    the two. The sys_vfork wrapper passes flags=16657 as the
    only non-zero argument.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side vfork is significantly
    cheaper than fork because CLONE_VM skips the page-table COW
    setup - the child runs in the parent's address space directly.
    CLONE_VFORK adds a completion-wait for the child to exec or
    exit. Historically vfork was used as a perf-optimization for
    exec workloads; modern posix_spawn() is the preferred
    replacement.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    vfork is subject to the same RLIMIT_NPROC and cgroup limits
    as fork. The shared-address-space window between vfork and
    the child's exec is a classic foot-gun - any data write in
    the child corrupts the parent's address space. POSIX
    explicitly prohibits the child from doing anything other
    than _exit() or exec*() before the parent resumes. These
    rules are caller-side discipline, not enforced by the
    kernel.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 220
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
High-level Unix-portable syscall wrappers (dispatcher-exposed names)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX read(2) on Linux ARM64. The
    dispatcher exposes the bare name syscall_read across all 18 supported
    platforms; this is the arm64 implementation. Routes through
    syscall_3 (the 3-arg inline-asm trampoline declared earlier in this
    file) with the asm-generic __NR_read (63) and the standard read(2)
    argument shape (fd, buf, count). Return value is bytes_read on
    success or negative -errno on failure, matching kernel ABI exactly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_READ() to fetch the syscall number (returns 63), then
    invokes syscall_3 with (63, fd, buf, count). The inline-asm in
    syscall_3 loads 63 into x8, fd into x0, buf into x1, count into x2,
    issues svc #0, and returns the kernel's x0 result. No additional
    error translation; -errno is propagated to the caller verbatim.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two procedure-call layers (syscall_read → syscall_3) plus one
    svc #0. The procedure-call overhead is the typical Runa
    Process-invocation cost (~one prologue/epilogue pair); the kernel
    side cost dominates for any non-trivial read (file lookup, buffer
    copy). Inliner may collapse syscall_read to a direct syscall_3
    invocation when called in a hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd, buf, and count are passed through to the kernel unchanged. The
    kernel validates fd against the per-process file-descriptor table
    and buf+count against the calling process's address space (via
    access_ok / copy_to_user). This proc does no validation of its own;
    bad pointers or out-of-range fds produce kernel -EBADF / -EFAULT
    sentinels that the caller must check.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_READ()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buf, count)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX write(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Mirrors syscall_read in surface: 3-arg shape (fd, buf, count),
    returns bytes_written or -errno. Asm-generic __NR_write is 64.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_WRITE() (returns 64), then linux_arm64_syscall_3(64, fd, buf, count).
    Loads 64 into x8, args into x0/x1/x2, svc #0, returns x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Identical performance profile to syscall_read: two Process-call
    layers + one svc. The kernel-side write path dominates for any
    non-trivial buffer (page-cache copy or device-driver path).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Identical to syscall_read: fd validated by kernel against the FD
    table, buf+count validated against the calling address space. No
    proc-side validation; bad inputs surface as -EBADF/-EFAULT.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_WRITE()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buf, count)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX open(2) on Linux ARM64. The
    asm-generic numbering omits __NR_open; this proc bridges the legacy
    3-arg open() shape to the 4-arg openat() shape by prepending
    AT_FDCWD (-100) to the argument list and invoking __NR_openat (56)
    via syscall_4. The semantic guarantee POSIX makes for open(path,
    flags, mode) is preserved exactly: relative paths resolve from cwd,
    mode is applied to newly-created files, returned fd is non-negative
    on success or -errno on failure.

    Reference: include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h pins AT_FDCWD = -100 (sign-
    extended to a 64-bit register on arm64).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_OPEN() (returns 56, the __NR_openat number on
    asm-generic). Invokes linux_arm64_syscall_4(56, -100, filename, flags, mode):
    loads 56 into x8, AT_FDCWD (-100) into x0, filename pointer into
    x1, flags into x2, mode into x3, issues svc #0, returns x0.
    Bridging from the 3-arg open() shape to the 4-arg openat() shape
    happens here; downstream callers do not need to know about the
    arm64 native-syscall difference.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One additional register load (AT_FDCWD constant) compared to a
    native open() syscall on x86_64. Kernel-side cost is identical:
    arm64 openat with AT_FDCWD invokes the same do_filp_open path as
    x86_64 open. Net overhead vs native: 1 mov instruction in
    user space.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Path resolution, permission checks (file mode, parent-dir
    traversal), and O_CREAT mode-vs-umask masking are all kernel
    responsibilities. This proc forwards filename verbatim as a
    user-pointer; the kernel runs copy_from_user / strncpy_from_user
    bounded by PATH_MAX. Bad pointers produce -EFAULT.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_OPEN()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_4(syscall_num, 0 minus 100, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX close(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Single-arg shape (fd), returns 0 on success or -errno. Asm-generic
    __NR_close is 57.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_CLOSE() (returns 57), then linux_arm64_syscall_1(57, fd). Loads 57
    into x8, fd into x0, svc #0, returns x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One Process-call layer + one svc. Kernel-side cost dominated by
    the FD-table slot release and any associated inode-refcount
    decrement.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd is validated against the process FD table by the kernel.
    Closing an already-closed fd returns -EBADF; closing a half-shut
    socket may trigger a TCP RST per the socket's lingering options.
    These are kernel-side semantic concerns, not proc-side input
    validation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX _exit(2) on Linux ARM64. This
    terminates only the calling thread (Linux semantics for plain
    __NR_exit (93) is per-thread; __NR_exit_group (94) terminates the
    whole process). On a single-threaded process this is observably
    indistinguishable from process termination. Multi-threaded callers
    that want to terminate the entire process must invoke
    sys_exit_group (already declared above) instead.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_EXIT() (returns 93), then linux_arm64_syscall_1(93, status). Loads
    93 into x8, status into x0, svc #0. The kernel does not return
    from exit; control transfers to do_exit and the calling thread is
    reaped. The Return statement below is unreachable but required
    syntactically for the Process declaration.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single-shot terminal call. The svc dispatches into do_exit which
    walks the thread's resources (file descriptors, memory mappings,
    signal handlers) and releases them. Cost is proportional to
    resource ownership, not to anything this proc controls.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Exit status is propagated to the parent via wait*(2). No
    user-space validation needed; the kernel accepts any 32-bit
    integer as exit status (the low 8 bits are observable to the
    parent via WEXITSTATUS).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_EXIT()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for the brk(2) heap-management syscall
    on Linux ARM64. Asm-generic __NR_brk is 214. The Linux brk(2) ABI
    returns the new program break (top of the data segment) on
    success, or the current break unchanged if addr cannot be honoured
    — never -errno. Callers must compare returned value to requested
    addr to detect failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_BRK() (returns 214), then linux_arm64_syscall_1(214, addr). Loads
    214 into x8, addr into x0, svc #0, returns x0 (the actual new
    break, possibly equal to the old break on failure).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) kernel path when extending or shrinking the brk inside an
    already-allocated VMA range. May trigger a VMA-extend path
    requiring acquisition of the mmap_lock; in heavily-threaded
    processes this can contend.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The kernel rejects requests that would collide with the stack
    region, that exceed RLIMIT_DATA, or that would unmap regions
    holding live memory. No proc-side validation; the kernel's
    do_brk_flags is the gatekeeper.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_BRK()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX mmap(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Asm-generic __NR_mmap is 222. Unlike i386's mmap which packs all 6
    args into a struct, arm64 mmap takes 6 register args directly
    (no offset-shift, no struct indirection). Returns the mapped
    virtual address on success or a negative value in the -errno
    range (e.g., -ENOMEM = -12) on failure; callers must detect failure
    by comparison against MAP_FAILED (-1 cast to pointer) or by
    interpreting any value in [-4095, -1] as -errno.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_MMAP() (returns 222), then linux_arm64_syscall_6(222, addr, length,
    prot, flags, fd, offset). Loads 222 into x8, addr/length/prot/
    flags/fd/offset into x0..x5, svc #0, returns x0. The kernel's
    arm64 sys_mmap entry in arch/arm64/kernel/sys.c is a thin shim
    around mm/mmap.c::ksys_mmap_pgoff that does NOT shift offset by
    PAGE_SHIFT (unlike the legacy mmap2 syscall on 32-bit arches);
    offset is interpreted as a byte offset.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Six register loads + one svc. Kernel-side cost depends heavily on
    flags: anonymous-private mappings are cheap (just VMA allocation),
    file-backed mappings invoke the filesystem's mmap method and may
    trigger readahead, MAP_POPULATE forces pre-faulting of all pages
    inline (O(length / PAGE_SIZE)).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    prot bits and flags are validated by the kernel (e.g., PROT_EXEC
    + MAP_ANONYMOUS may be rejected under SELinux execmem policy);
    fd is validated against the FD table; offset must be page-aligned.
    No proc-side validation; bad inputs surface as -EINVAL.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_MMAP()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX munmap(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Asm-generic __NR_munmap is 215. Two-arg shape (addr, length).
    Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure. addr must be
    page-aligned; length is rounded up to the next page boundary.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_MUNMAP() (returns 215), then linux_arm64_syscall_2(215, addr,
    length). Loads 215 into x8, addr into x0, length into x1, svc #0,
    returns x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cost is O(length / PAGE_SIZE) for TLB shootdown + page-table
    teardown. On many-CPU systems with the region cross-CPU-shared,
    TLB shootdown IPI cost dominates and scales with online CPU count.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Unmapping a region not currently mapped returns -EINVAL.
    Unmapping a region partially overlapping a VMA splits the VMA;
    no security consequence beyond memory-availability changes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX fstat(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Asm-generic __NR_fstat is 80 (note: this IS present in
    asm-generic, unlike __NR_stat which was removed). Two-arg shape
    (fd, statbuf). Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure. Writes
    the struct stat into the user-space buffer pointed to by statbuf.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_FSTAT() (returns 80), then linux_arm64_syscall_2(80, fd, statbuf).
    Loads 80 into x8, fd into x0, statbuf into x1, svc #0, returns x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) kernel-side: one FD-table lookup + one inode-metadata copy
    into the user buffer. No I/O for cached inodes; potentially one
    disk read for cold inodes (rare).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd is validated against the FD table; statbuf is validated
    against the calling address space (copy_to_user). No proc-side
    validation; bad inputs return -EBADF or -EFAULT.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX lseek(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Asm-generic __NR_lseek is 62. Three-arg shape (fd, offset,
    whence). Returns the resulting file offset on success or -errno
    on failure. Offset is signed 64-bit on arm64 (no need for the
    32-bit _llseek shim that 32-bit arches use).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls linux_arm64_SYS_LSEEK() (returns 62), then linux_arm64_syscall_3(62, fd, offset,
    whence). Loads 62 into x8, fd into x0, offset into x1, whence
    into x2, svc #0, returns x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) kernel-side for seekable files: one FD-table lookup + one
    f_pos field update. Pipes/sockets/character-special files
    return -ESPIPE without further cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd is validated against the FD table; whence must be in
    {SEEK_SET=0, SEEK_CUR=1, SEEK_END=2} (or the extended values
    SEEK_DATA=3, SEEK_HOLE=4 on filesystems that support them);
    offset must be representable in off_t. Kernel handles validation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Linux ARM64.
    Asm-generic __NR_ioctl is 29 (include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h,
    Linux mainline). Three-arg shape (fd, request, argp) where the
    third argument is either an integer or a pointer to a request-
    specific structure (e.g. struct winsize for TIOCGWINSZ, struct
    termios for TCGETS). Returns the device-specific result on
    success, -errno on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling linux_arm64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns 29)
    and linux_arm64_syscall_3(29, fd, cmd, arg). The AArch64 SVC
    convention loads 29 into x8, fd into x0, cmd into x1, arg into x2,
    then svc #0; the kernel returns the result in x0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the kernel — one FD-table lookup and a driver
    vtable jump per request. Driver-side cost is request-dependent;
    terminal queries (TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ) are cheap memcpy-from-tty
    operations. Callers should batch related queries (e.g. cache the
    TIOCGWINSZ result for the lifetime of an ncurses-style frame).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The kernel validates fd against the FD table and dispatches cmd
    through the device's file_operations.unlocked_ioctl vtable. The
    arg pointer, if non-zero, is dereferenced by the kernel with the
    structure size implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to
    match (struct termios = 60 bytes on arm64, struct winsize = 8
    bytes). Negative returns indicate -errno and must be treated as
    failure.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let syscall_num be linux_arm64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return linux_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POSIX file-mode constants (decimal-encoded octal modes)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "linux_arm64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    POSIX file-mode constant 0644 in octal = 420 in decimal. Bit
    layout: owner=rw- (6 = 110), group=r-- (4 = 100), other=r-- (4 =
    100). This is the conventional mode for regular files created by
    user-space tools (matches the default of e.g. install(1) without
    -m, and is the most common explicit mode passed to open(2) with
    O_CREAT or to creat(2)). Pre-decoded to decimal because Runa's
    lexer does not accept C-style octal-prefix literals; expressing
    file modes as decimal integers is the canonical workaround.

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 sys/stat.h: S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200,
    S_IRGRP=0040, S_IROTH=0004. Sum = 0644 = 420.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the decimal integer 420. Compile-time constant; no
    runtime computation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable. The kernel-side cost of
    applying this mode in creat()/openat()/mkdirat() is independent
    of how the mode value reaches the syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mode argument is masked by the calling process's umask
    before being applied to the new inode. Callers that need the
    exact 0644 mode unmasked must explicitly fchmod() after creation
    or arrange for a zero umask. This proc does not perform that
    arrangement; it returns the raw mode value.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 420
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    POSIX file-mode constant 0755 in octal = 493 in decimal. Bit
    layout: owner=rwx (7 = 111), group=r-x (5 = 101), other=r-x (5
    = 101). This is the conventional mode for executables and
    directories created by user-space tools (matches default of
    install(1) -m 0755, mkdir(1) without explicit -m on most umask
    settings). Pre-decoded to decimal for the same reason as
    MODE_0644.

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 sys/stat.h: S_IRWXU=0700, S_IRGRP=0040,
    S_IXGRP=0010, S_IROTH=0004, S_IXOTH=0001. Sum = 0755 = 493.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the decimal integer 493. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same umask interaction as MODE_0644. For directories created with
    mkdirat(2), the umask is applied; for executables the typical
    umask of 022 yields the same 0755 mode by coincidence (0755 &
    ~022 = 0755). Callers that explicitly want 0755 regardless of
    umask must chmod after creation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 493
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
lseek whence constants (SEEK_SET / SEEK_CUR / SEEK_END)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "linux_arm64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    POSIX lseek(2) whence value selecting absolute-offset addressing:
    the file offset is set to the offset argument verbatim, counted
    from the beginning of the file. Linux asm-generic uses the same
    value as Linux x86_64 (SEEK_SET = 0), and POSIX requires this
    value across all conforming systems.

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h, Linux include/uapi/linux/fs.h:
    SEEK_SET = 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 0. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant value, no user input. The kernel validates whence in
    lseek(2); supplying a value outside {SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, SEEK_END,
    SEEK_DATA, SEEK_HOLE} returns -EINVAL.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    POSIX lseek(2) whence value selecting relative-offset addressing:
    the file offset is incremented (signed) by the offset argument,
    counted from the current file position. Asm-generic value matches
    Linux x86_64: SEEK_CUR = 1.

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h: SEEK_CUR = 1.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 1. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant value, no user input.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "linux_arm64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    POSIX lseek(2) whence value selecting end-relative addressing:
    the file offset is set to the file size plus the offset argument
    (negative offset seeks backward from end). Asm-generic value
    matches Linux x86_64: SEEK_END = 2.

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 unistd.h: SEEK_END = 2.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 2. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant value, no user input. Behaviour for files where the
    end-position is mutable (e.g., during concurrent writes) is
    defined by POSIX as undefined; the kernel resolves the seek
    atomically against the current i_size at syscall-entry time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 2
End Process
